Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

---

## Pattern Inventory

| API | Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|----------|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption | `CancellationToken` signaling |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop kill | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Blocking call | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |
| `while (true)` | `RunLoop()` | Cancellable work loop | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns immediately when either the event is
            // signaled OR the cancellation token fires — no need
            // for Thread.Interrupt to wake the thread.
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (index == 1) // token.WaitHandle fired → stop requested
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string? item = null;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                if (_queue.Count > 0)
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
            }

            if (item is not null)
                Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // signals token.WaitHandle → unblocks WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit
        // No Thread.Abort fallback needed — the loop checks the
        // token and exits cooperatively.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

## What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop must cooperate with cancellation |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Unblocks on **either** new-item signal or cancellation — replaces `Thread.Interrupt` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Interrupt` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9); token signaling is the modern replacement |
| `Thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+; cooperative exit makes it unnecessary |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` must be disposed to avoid timer/handle leaks |

---

## Pre-existing Bug Fixed

The original code has a **lost-signal race**: if two rapid `Enqueue` calls both `Set()` the event before `RunLoop` calls `Reset()`, only **one** item is dequeued — the second sits in the queue until the next enqueue. The migrated code fixes this with the `_queue.Count > 0` guard, but for a production system consider replacing the entire `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` with `BlockingCollection<T>`:

```csharp
// Even simpler — BlockingCollection handles all synchronization
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
                Handle(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { /* expected on shutdown */ }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _thread?.Join(5000);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

## Key Pitfalls to Watch

1. **`Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — there is no workaround; the code *must* cooperate via `CancellationToken`.
2. **`WaitOne` doesn't check tokens** — you must use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle`, or the thread stays blocked forever after cancellation.
3. **Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — leaking it causes timer and callback leaks, especially with `CancelAfter`.
4. **Cancellation is not immediate** — it only takes effect at the next checkpoint (`WaitAny` return, `ThrowIfCancellationRequested`, loop condition). If `Handle(item)` is long-running, pass the token into it too.
5. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — only catch it at the top-level orchestration point (like `RunLoop`), not deep in the call chain.
